## Naming Evaluation (First Priority)

- `nextGeneration` clearly describes the function's purpose (compute the next Game of Life generation). Keep.
- `liveCells`, `liveKeys`, `neighborCounts`, `survives`, `keyOf` all clearly reveal intent.

Naming decision: Keep current names.

## Initial APP Mass

Counting components in `nextGeneration` (the main function under test):

```typescript
export function nextGeneration(liveCells: Cell[]): Cell[] {
  const liveKeys = new Set(liveCells.map(keyOf));
  const neighborCounts = new Map<string, { cell: Cell; count: number }>();

  for (const [x, y] of liveCells) {
    for (const [dx, dy] of NEIGHBOR_OFFSETS) {
      const cell: Cell = [x + dx, y + dy];
      const k = keyOf(cell);
      const entry = neighborCounts.get(k);
      if (entry) {
        entry.count++;
      } else {
        neighborCounts.set(k, { cell, count: 1 });
      }
    }
  }

  const survives = (k: string, count: number): boolean =>
    count === 3 || (count === 2 && liveKeys.has(k));

  return Array.from(neighborCounts)
    .filter(([k, { count }]) => survives(k, count))
    .map(([, { cell }]) => cell);
}
```

- Constants: `1` (count: 1), `3`, `2`, `3` (in survives) = ~4
- Bindings: liveCells, liveKeys, neighborCounts, x, y, dx, dy, cell, k, entry, survives, count = ~12
- Invocations: `new Set`, `liveCells.map(keyOf)`, `new Map`, `keyOf(cell)`, `neighborCounts.get`, `neighborCounts.set`, `liveKeys.has`, `Array.from`, `.filter`, `.map`, `survives()` = ~11
- Conditionals: `if (entry)`, `count === 3`, `||`, `count === 2`, `&&` = ~3-5 (counting `if` and ternary-like)
- Loops: 2 `for...of` loops, plus `.map`, `.filter`, `.map` on Array.from = ~5 loops
- Assignments: `entry.count++` = 1

